# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The **1777 New York gubernatorial election** was held in June 1777 to elect the governor and the lieutenant governor.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The election began on June 1, but due to the American Revolution it took some time to collect and count the votes, and the official result was announced on July 9.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] George Clinton accepted the office of Governor on July 11 and assumed its duties immediately, pending to take the oath as soon as he could safely leave his military command.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] There were no parties yet, as the Democratic-Republican and Federalist Parties appeared only in 1792.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Until then the candidacies were based on personal recognition.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The concepts of "running mates" also did not apply in this election, with candidates running separately for Governor and Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The New York Committee of Safety endorsed Philip Schuyler for Governor and George Clinton for Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] George Clinton was elected both Governor and Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Clinton formally resigned the lieutenant governorship, leaving a vacancy.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] State Senator Pierre Van Cortlandt was elected *President pro tempore* of the State Senate, and acted as Lieutenant Governor until the end of the legislative year.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1777-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Van Cortlandt was then elected in a special election and took office as Lieutenant Governor on June 30, 1778.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in New York from April 29 to May 1, 1783.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] George Clinton, the incumbent governor, defeated Philip Schuyler, the surveyor general, and Ephraim Paine, the senator from the middle district.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In March 1783, the New York legislature repealed the act granting all import duties to the United States government under the Articles of Confederation.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In its place, the legislature passed a law granting such duties but restricting their collection and reserving the power of appointment of collecting officers to the state of New York.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The tariff duties issue, along with the ongoing debate over the new Constitution of the United States, formed the basis for the early development of political factions in the state.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The import duties, which were incredibly valuable given the prominence of the Port of New York City, formed the basis of a larger debate over the nature of New York's sovereignty and association with the other independent American states.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The nationalist faction, which supported the unrestricted grant of duties to the United States, was led by Alexander Hamilton, John Jay, Robert R.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Livingston, Philip Schuyler, and the Van Rensselaer family.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The opposition was led by Governor George Clinton, who had served in the state's highest office since its establishment following the Revolution with little opposition, having been returned unanimously in 1780.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] His supporters included Robert Yates, John Lansing, and Melancton Smith.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1783-new-york-gubernatorial-election] These factions are informally known as the Federalists and anti-Federalists, respectively.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The **1789 New York gubernatorial election** was held in April 1789 to elect the Governor of New York for a term beginning in July 1789.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Governor George Clinton was narrowly re-elected to a fifth consecutive term in office over Robert Yates.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] From the establishment of an independent government of New York in 1777, George Clinton had continuously served in the office of Governor; he had no opponent in 1780 or 1786.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] During that previous decade, New York politics had coalesced around two loose factions: a federalist faction led by Alexander Hamilton, John Jay, Robert R.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Livingston, Philip Schuyler, and the Van Rensselaer family, which favored adoption of the proposed United States Constitution and an anti-federalist faction led by Governor Clinton, Robert Yates, John Lansing, and Melancton Smith, which opposed ratification without serious revision.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] At the New York convention to ratify the Constitution in 1788, Clinton presided over a sharp division between the federalists and anti-federalists.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The final vote favored ratification of the Constitution as written by a vote of 30–27.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Clinton, despite his anti-federalist views, closed the convention by vowing to exercise his office to enforce it and maintain order.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] However, partisan divisions were sharpened by the formation of a new national administration under President George Washington, who sought to elevate Hamilton, Jay, and other federalists to his administration without representation for the Clinton faction.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] For the first time, the federalist faction actively organized to block Clinton's re-election.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In light of the incumbent's broad popularity, they sought to nominate an anti-federalist in order to divide the majority faction.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] At a meeting in New York City on February 11, they appointed a committee of correspondence to manage the campaign, consisting of Hamilton, William Duer, Robert Troup and anti-federalist Aaron Burr, who defected to oppose Clinton.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The meeting nominated Supreme Court justice Robert Yates.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] On February 24, Yates accepted the nomination.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] There was a movement to nominate Richard Morris, who was favored by the majority within the federalist faction, but he declined to be a candidate on February 27.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Pierre Van Cortlandt was the only candidate for Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Clinton was re-elected to a fifth term in office, albeit by the lowest margin to date.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] In his home county of Ulster, Clinton won 1,039 out of 1,245 votes.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-new-york-gubernatorial-election] However, federalists won a majority of the seats in the New York Assembly.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The **1789 United States House of Representatives elections in New York** were held on March 3 and 4, 1789, to elect 6 U.S.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives to represent the State of New York in the 1st United States Congress.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of U.S.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Constitution on July 26, 1788, by a very slim margin.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] On January 27, 1789, the New York State Legislature divided the State of New York into six congressional districts which were not numbered.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Three Federalists and three Anti-Federalists (later known as the Democratic-Republicans) were elected.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Note: This was the first time political parties appeared in the United States.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Before the question of establishing a federal government, or not, arose, all candidatures had been personal.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Now, politicians aligned in two opposing groups: First those in favor of the establishment of a federal government and those against it, and then - after the federal government had been indeed established - those who supported it and those who did not.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The 1st United States Congress had convened at Federal Hall in New York City on March 4, 1789, without any members from the State of New York, and without a quorum in either Senate or House.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The first day with a quorum in the House was April 1.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The representatives elected in and near New York City took their seats soon after the election.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The upstate representatives needed some time to arrive, and Peter Silvester took his seat on April 22, John Hathorn on April 23, and Jeremiah Van Rensselaer on May 9.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] In April 1790, all six representatives ran for re-election: Floyd, Hathorn and Van Rensselaer (all Dem.-Rep.) were defeated; Laurance, Benson and Silvester (all Fed.) were re-elected.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] The **1789 United States Senate election in New York** was held in July 1789 to elect two U.S. senators to represent the State of New York in the United States Senate.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish the proceedings how to elect the senators.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the First United States Congress for March 4, 1789, and the election of U.S. senators and U.S. representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Both sides expected to win the State election in April.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On June 4, Governor George Clinton called an extra session of the State Legislature to convene on July 6 at City Hall in Albany, New York.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] At the state election in April 1789, for a term beginning on July 1, a large Federalist majority had been elected to the New York State Assembly (65 members), estimated by State Senator James Duane at 42 to 22.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] The New York State Senate (24 members) continued with a slim Federalist majority.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] The 13th New York State Legislature (term 1789–90) convened on July 6, and on July 11 passed *"An act directing the manner of electing Senators to represent this State in the Senate of the United States"*, which required the election to be made by "concurrent vote" of both houses of the Legislature.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] This meant, if only one U.S. senator was to be elected, that each house nominated a candidate, and if both houses nominated the same person ("concurred"), the nominee was elected.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] If the Assembly nominated one, the Senate another, then the Senate's nominee was voted upon in the Assembly and the Assembly's nominee in the Senate; if none of the nominees was accepted by the other house, the proceedings started at the beginning.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] If two U.S. senators were to be elected, and Assembly and Senate chose different nominees, then the Assembly should elect one of the two Senate nominees, and the Senate one of the two Assembly nominees, effectively leaving one seat to be filled by each house of the Legislature.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On July 13, the law was submitted to the Council of Revision.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Thus the law was vetoed, and the State Legislature was left to fill the seats without written rules.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] In practice, the Assembly and the Senate separately took a vote, and if the winner in both houses was the same, he was declared elected.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] If Assembly and Senate chose different persons, the houses met for a joint ballot, which occurred for the first time in 1802.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On July 16, after the Council of Revision had vetoed the law, State Senator Philip Schuyler and Assemblyman Rufus King, two Federalists, were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Senate by a joint resolution of both houses of the State Legislature.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments, which consisted of the governor of New York and four state senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the Council.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-york] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1790 Connecticut gubernatorial election** was held on April 8, 1790, in order to elect the Governor of Connecticut.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Federalist Governor of Connecticut Samuel Huntington won re-election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 8, 1790, Federalist nominee Samuel Huntington easily won re-election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Huntington was sworn in for his fifth term on May 11, 1790.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The **1790 United States House of Representatives elections in New York** were held from April 27 to 29, 1790, to elect six U.S.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives to represent the State of New York in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives under the United States Constitution had been elected in March 1789, and had taken their seats in the 1st United States Congress for a term ending on March 3, 1791.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Nevertheless, the New York politicians chose to have the seats filled, in case there might be a special session to convene at an earlier date.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The districts remained the same as for the previous elections in March 1789.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Five Federalists and one Anti-Federalist (later known as the Democratic-Republicans) were elected.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The incumbents Laurance, Benson and Silvester were re-elected, the incumbents Floyd, Hathorn and Van Rensselaer were defeated.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Note: At this time political parties were still very new in the United States.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Politicians aligned in two opposing groups: Those supporting the federal government and those opposing it.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representative-elect James Townsend died on May 24, 1790, just a month after his election, and well before the congressional term began.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] A special election to fill the vacancy was held at the time of the annual state election, from April 26 to 28, 1791, and was won by Anti-Federalist Thomas Tredwell.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Thus four Federalists and two Anti-Federalists represented New York in the House of Representatives of the 2nd U.S.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The House of Representatives of the 2nd United States Congress convened for its first session at Congress Hall in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791, and Gordon, Laurance, Silvester and Tredwell took their seats on this day.
[src:1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Benson took his seat on November 4; and Schoonmaker at some time between November 15, 1791, and January 30, 1792.
